reviews.author: A Aguirre
reviews.text: Really cold water on a cloudy day. Hard to access because of stairways. Needs more upkeep

reviews.author: Fernando Augusto Sanchez
reviews.text: This beach is private...it is located behind the Morro, and can be reached via the Spider Pass, which is reached by walking along the rugged coast from the Horseshoe, bordering the cliffs of the Morro...on this beach there are vestiges of a tower from the time of the war between Chile and Peru...

reviews.author: Raul Hayball
reviews.text: The route to La Chira via La Herradura beach is adventurous and of medium risk. The beach itself is pretty, clean, the sea is rough. I haven't seen any swimmers. It doesn't have any services and the AAHH population is at the back on the hill. I don't know how safe it is.

reviews.author: Edgar Poe
reviews.text: An adventure to get to this beach, I definitely had a lot of fun

reviews.author: Ricardo Respaldiza
reviews.text: I went for a run on this beach and spent a pleasant moment of peace and tranquility. The sound of the beautiful sea and the absence of people allows it to be clean.

name: Cruz del Papa
address: RXJ7+QVR, Cima del Morro Solar, Chorrillos 15064, Peru

reviews.author: Brian Cooper
reviews.text: I love walking from San Miguel to this spot in Chorrillos! It's a bit secluded and a little bit steep of a climb, but the view is fantastic. Close by are the planetarium, the statue of Christ of the Pacific, and the higher points of the communication antennas at about 1.2k meters altitude. Be sure to take water with you if you go on up from the cross tower, as it's not always available. Many bikers use the great trails out in the morro.

reviews.author: Damon McNeil
reviews.text: This place is really cool. It provides a good lookout of the ocean and a good bit of Lima. The cross is pretty cool when lit up at night, however, this is a pretty sketchy place to be at night. I would only recommend being there at night if you are with a pretty large group. We were in a group of 5 and were warned by a kid that if we walked up the road much further from here, we'd definitely get mugged. It makes for nice pics though, so it could be worth it :)

reviews.author: Rob -
reviews.text:
Our English speaking guide was wonderful. We learnt so much. The staff do a fantastic job looking after the reserve. Plenty of birds and other wildlife to see.

You can only explore the reserve with a guide. I recommend booking the boat tour.

reviews.author: jorge Lazo
reviews.text: Relax

reviews.author: Jose Carlos Munoz Arellano

reviews.author: Scarlet Salas
reviews.text:
I really expected much more from this place. The hike isn't much, as it's quick and there isn't much to see along the way. The most worthwhile option is the catamaran ride, which costs extra and is where you can actually see a few more birds, although I don't know if it was when I went in late May when there were few more because it was autumn. The most abundant are the red-crested pochards and vultures, which were abundant. Admission is by group, and in my case, it took a while because there were only two guides.
The wetland, because they indicated it's not a swamp, is organized and clean. But for the entrance fee plus the extras you have to pay, it seems expensive to me, as what you'll see isn't dazzling. You'll see more birds in the adjacent areas and in that neighborhood, which is on the side, called Brisas de Villa.

It's very expensive for entertainment. Note that children under 5 also get bored quickly.

reviews.text: The Hidden Grotto of Chorrillos, the place is very beautiful, it is worth the effort that has to be made to get there, but it is worth it. It is a 30 to 40 minute path from La Chira Beach, along the cliff, this path is a little dangerous, in most sections, so you have to do it calmly, in the area apart from the Grotto, you will find many caves, preferably visiting in a group.

reviews.author: Thilo Boeck
reviews.text: Calm water and rather clean beach during weekdays. In summer it gets really crowded but nice and relaxed

reviews.author: Marco
reviews.text: Nice beach and fish market

reviews.author: Francisco R-58
reviews.text: A very nice place. The municipality organizes sports activities. It's recommended to go in the mornings rather than in the afternoons. Although there aren't many restaurants nearby, the only one is the seafood restaurant next door. If you want to eat something else, you have to walk up several blocks to barely find a restaurant. And at the main entrance, on the left side as you enter, there's a very, very neglected area.

reviews.author: Alexander Geyrhofer
reviews.text: I can't understand anyone who likes the beach.  Firstly, right on the street, crowded and extremely loud. Apparently everyone wants to be the best DJ and turns up the boombox, regardless of whether anyone wants to hear it or not. Umbrella costs 30 soles per day. Some beach vendor is shouting every minute. So you can't relax there.

reviews.author: Miguel MejÃ­a Castro
reviews.text: One of Peru's most beautiful popular beaches. It's part of the Costa Verde circuit, and I recommend visiting Monday through Friday, starting at 4 p.m., as it's very crowded on Saturdays and Sundays. Photo: @miguelmejiacastro

name: La Granja Villa
address: Av. Alameda del Premio Real 397, Chorrillos 15067, Peru

reviews.author: Lisandra Braz
reviews.text: We had a wonderful day. Perfect place to spend the day with kids in Lima. We went as a family group ages from 2-17 kids/teens and 42-74 adults. Everyone had a great time with games, rides, the pools, and waterslides. We also enjoyed visiting the farm animals. We spend >6h and didn't see everything (mostly because we spend a lot of time in the waterpark).

reviews.author: Lizett Canari
reviews.text: Such a cute place to visit with the kiddos, a lot of restrictions around pools unlike waterparks in other countries, e.g no walking with shoes or must have bathing suits on before walking inside pool area and no using hot tub after 4pm on weekdays, but putting those aside definetely makes it worth going with the kids for a nice outing.

reviews.author: Samuel Zavaletta
reviews.text: A small amusement park. They've got some animals, and you can feed them food you buy at the park, so that was nice. It's not in a good part of town though.

reviews.text: More than worth it!!! Only a $20 all access pass!!!! Lots of fun and big!!! The earlier you arrive the best it is to take advantage of everything there is to do in there!!!

reviews.author: Ruben Caminos
reviews.text: Total chaos, an elderly manager over 80 years old, his secretary is a street vendor who sells at the door. Total improvisation. This is my third Sunday because they open whenever they want at 11 am and there are no tickets. I posted a complaint because on social media they claim that tickets are sold just before the show, but that's not the case. Children are the most disadvantaged. Tickets cost 10 soles even though the ticket says "donation S/6." We got a third shift at the insistence of a group of people. That day there were easily more than 120 people, and this is a private association. A lot of money comes in without declaring income.

reviews.text:
A wonderful experience. I went with my then 4-year-old son. I would go again at least once every year and a half.
The dome you enter is small, and the explanations are very good, as is the music selection. They leave you with a few questions or brief inquiries so you can personally search for more information, and that's invaluable because it inspires you to want to know more.

It has a small museum where you can take photos.

reviews.author: Elias Chelala (Chewy)
reviews.text:
Monumento al Soldado Desconocido is a poignant and thought-provoking memorial that pays homage to the unknown soldiers who sacrificed their lives for a greater cause. Situated in a serene and well-maintained park, the monument exudes a sense of solemnity and respect.

The design of the monument is both striking and evocative, capturing the essence of the anonymous heroes it commemorates. The intricate details and symbolism incorporated into the sculpture provoke deep reflection on the profound impact of war and the sacrifices made by countless individuals who remain nameless.

The surrounding landscape adds to the overall ambiance, providing a peaceful setting for contemplation. The well-kept gardens and pathways create a tranquil environment, allowing visitors to pay their respects in a setting that encourages quiet introspection.

What sets this monument apart is its ability to convey a universal message about the collective sacrifice of soldiers, transcending national boundaries. It serves as a reminder that, regardless of nationality or background, the human cost of conflict is shared by all.

Visitors will appreciate the informative plaques and displays that offer historical context, enriching the experience with a deeper understanding of the monument's significance. The accessibility of the site, along with clear signage, makes it easy for both locals and tourists to find and appreciate this meaningful tribute.

Monumento al Soldado Desconocido is more than just a physical structure; it's a testament to the enduring spirit of those who gave their all without recognition. Whether you come to reflect on the history it represents or simply to enjoy the peaceful surroundings, this monument is a must-visit for anyone seeking a meaningful and contemplative experience.

reviews.author: Bo
reviews.text: This was the final destination for my biking tour from Miraflores to Chorillos. You have a great view of the city and the ocean at the top. The slope could be a bit steep for some bikers, but manageable for most. I recommend this if you want to explore places outside Miraflores.
